WEBVTT

00:12.290 --> 00:12.991
Good evening, everybody.

00:13.011 --> 00:13.491
How are you doing?

00:15.554 --> 00:15.654
Good.

00:15.674 --> 00:17.316
Thank you for making time in space.

00:19.058 --> 00:22.982
We'll talk a little bit about our relationship and our friendship.

00:23.122 --> 00:31.972
But in a lot of ways, this is just a beautiful gift to share what the life has been like between us for the last 12 or so years.

00:32.873 --> 00:41.042
And oftentimes, what starts out as a stranger or a neighbor has a potential to turn into a family and even more than friends.

00:41.474 --> 00:55.491
And so I believe that our dynamic is simply sharing with the bride what kinship can really look like and may it be a prophetic gift to the body to invite each other into the same spaces.

00:55.971 --> 01:02.299
So with that, I just wanna ask some questions to my brother and one of my dearest friends in the world, Kevin Chandler.

01:03.240 --> 01:08.527
So Kevin, can you give us a little backdrop or a little story of how you came and met Jesus?

01:09.348 --> 01:11.410
Yeah, hi guys, by the way.

01:12.258 --> 01:13.460
Great to see all of you here.

01:14.761 --> 01:29.180
So when I was six years old, I had spent at that point six years in the church and been around knowing who Jesus was.

01:29.320 --> 01:31.543
My dad was Adigen.

01:31.603 --> 01:37.350
My mom basically ran the Sunday school program and I was around it.

01:37.590 --> 01:40.594
But when I was six years old,

01:41.026 --> 01:42.548
thought, I'm going to go over this way.

01:42.728 --> 01:44.110
So the podium is sitting there.

01:44.450 --> 01:44.871
There we go.

01:46.633 --> 01:54.743
But I thought that I should be able to wrap my head around to turn at me and, you know, because that's a normal thing.

01:55.144 --> 01:58.328
I tried to do that with my daughter and tried to teach her on the Trinity.

01:58.868 --> 02:00.470
I watched everything fall out of her head.

02:00.570 --> 02:01.431
Yeah.

02:01.952 --> 02:08.660
And so I was having trouble sleeping because I was like, spending forever somewhere and not ending.

02:08.720 --> 02:10.002
That's just weird.

02:10.114 --> 02:26.753
And my dad, who knows me better than most, he sat me down on his bed, and instead of trying to explain the attorney to me, he introduced me to Jesus as the person I could spend the attorney to be with.

02:27.314 --> 02:38.226
And so that's when my personal walk with him began, and I would just say over the years with, you know,

02:38.370 --> 02:54.585
hospital stays and surgeries and friends coming and going and relationships and physical challenges and Jesus has been the constant, which is something we can get more into at some point.

02:54.645 --> 03:08.178
But I've been asked a lot in my life, like, have you ever been angry at God for being a wheelchair, for me being a wheelchair, not God.

03:08.706 --> 03:13.131
Although there is a verse about his throne having a real, so.

03:13.592 --> 03:23.104
But my response to that is I actually haven't, just because he has been the constant.

03:23.224 --> 03:29.131
He has been the one person who has not failed me.

03:29.491 --> 03:32.915
And that's something I'm so thankful for.

03:33.897 --> 03:38.322
Yeah, I think in light of that too, you tell stories regularly about how he

03:38.786 --> 03:45.515
is your secure identity and has produced a wholeness in you that doesn't feel like there's a lack.

03:45.535 --> 03:50.262
And I remember there's one story from your backpacking years where you're, I think, in Italy.

03:50.942 --> 03:51.303
France.

03:51.523 --> 03:52.024
France.

03:52.044 --> 03:52.424
Similar.

03:52.725 --> 03:54.167
There was a lot of spaces you were in.

03:54.207 --> 03:54.407
Yeah.

03:54.688 --> 03:55.669
Same saying, sorry.

03:57.151 --> 04:02.358
No, and you had people constantly wanting to pray for you because of what they saw.

04:03.139 --> 04:04.461
And can you tell a little bit about that?

04:05.402 --> 04:08.306
Yeah, so in 2016,

04:08.802 --> 04:16.772
Some friends and I decided that we wanted to go to Europe and everything we wanted to do was not going to be wheelchair accessible.

04:17.413 --> 04:27.345
So we decided to leave my wheelchair at home and these friends carried me in the backpacks that you saw Eric carrying me in yesterday.

04:27.926 --> 04:32.471
And imagine that for three weeks with no safety net.

04:33.353 --> 04:37.778
We had four different guys trading off throughout the day carrying me.

04:38.082 --> 04:47.411
And yeah, we had an experience where this group wanted to pray for my healing.

04:48.232 --> 04:57.961
And it really upset me because I was like, I've spent my whole life being approached like this.

04:58.481 --> 05:00.163
But I'm not in my wheelchair.

05:01.624 --> 05:07.410
Up until then, my friends and I had seen this as the miracle.

05:07.842 --> 05:10.867
And so it really kind of messed me up.

05:11.087 --> 05:19.902
And some of that conversation was, well, I'm praying that you have the faith to be healed.

05:20.523 --> 05:28.857
And something that came back to me from Peter's first letter.

05:29.037 --> 05:34.546
I think it's at the end of chapter one or beginning of chapter two, he refers to

05:34.850 --> 05:36.632
the outcome of your faith.

05:37.013 --> 05:40.958
And he says that the outcome of your faith is the salvation of your soul.

05:41.679 --> 05:45.585
And I was like, wow, I got that, you know?

05:46.205 --> 06:04.370
And this all that night really wrestling that out with the Lord and that wrestling turning into a dance of being reminded that I am his and that my soul is securing him and that's

06:04.482 --> 06:07.045
That's what matters.

06:07.065 --> 06:08.667
Yeah, man, I get to see that.

06:09.288 --> 06:12.591
A real up close and personal basis through our time together.

06:13.312 --> 06:15.415
But can you explain a little bit more about these friendships?

06:15.655 --> 06:21.842
I think they're unique and they're special and may be different than the way in which we've seen this conversation.

06:23.304 --> 06:32.114
Yeah, so a lot of people get to see those four friends through photos and videos and books.

06:32.354 --> 06:34.957
and stuff, these guys carrying me on their back.

06:36.319 --> 06:43.368
But really, that's kind of the extreme, you know, high flying adventure side of it.

06:43.969 --> 06:50.878
And in the everyday life, I don't use a backpack every day, as you might wonder.

06:51.299 --> 07:00.210
But I have maybe like eight or 10 guys out of time that are

07:00.610 --> 07:06.898
cycling through my day to day and being part of what we call my caregiving.

07:07.438 --> 07:17.290
So we have a different guy come every morning and get me up and ready for the day and Katie and I just don't know where she is.

07:17.691 --> 07:18.772
Oh, there you are.

07:18.952 --> 07:23.498
We just celebrated our five-year writing anniversary this weekend.

07:28.764 --> 07:30.386
And so things have

07:30.498 --> 07:33.442
changed a bit since being married.

07:34.203 --> 07:43.575
But before I was married, I lived with a couple of guys and then they helped with taking care of me.

07:43.776 --> 07:52.707
And then throughout the week, we'd have different guys come and get me up or stay overnight or hang out during the day and had a coffee shop.

07:52.727 --> 07:57.714
Then they hung out at that had a bunch of guys working that could help out as well.

07:57.922 --> 08:07.315
And it was really just this awesome community of just weaving together our lives.

08:08.296 --> 08:21.293
And it wasn't just to make my life possible, but really worth living in some ways, like these relationships were and are so rich.

08:21.554 --> 08:24.558
And Eric has been a part of that as well.

08:25.259 --> 08:27.762
And now being married,

08:28.258 --> 08:57.298
We still have guys coming to get me up in the morning and we also There's a lot of responsibilities that You know taking care of our home that I can't physically do and so these guys actually step in and are in that way kind of part of our marriage and part of my role as a husband to fix this or you know take care of this thing or run this area and

08:57.506 --> 09:03.755
I get to do those things because of them, which has been a really cool experience.

09:04.576 --> 09:13.869
Even just making the bed, you know, we were talking earlier about how every guy that gets me up in the morning makes the bed differently, but they're making the bed.

09:13.889 --> 09:15.151
You tell a lot about that.

09:15.311 --> 09:16.232
You tell a lot about someone.

09:16.453 --> 09:17.815
Yeah.

09:18.135 --> 09:25.906
But through these friendships, it's, you know, I've found and we'll get more into this when we talk more about

09:26.242 --> 09:50.712
Eric and I in our friendship, but what starts as an invitation to take care of my needs becomes a deeper friendship, deeper relationship and brotherhood in which I get to care for them as well, because as my needs are being met, I don't have to worry about those.

09:51.133 --> 09:55.378
Instead, I get to turn all my attention and focus

09:55.746 --> 09:57.127
on to them.

09:57.147 --> 10:00.691
I don't have to self-advocate or self-care.

10:00.991 --> 10:11.882
I can completely abandon myself and put them first, which as we'll talk about later, the Bible talks a lot about putting others first.

10:13.084 --> 10:13.504
Yeah, man.

10:13.564 --> 10:18.329
And I think something that everybody wants to know about you and Katie is how did you guys meet?

10:18.509 --> 10:21.492
Because your love story is pretty spectacular.

10:22.053 --> 10:23.154
Yeah.

10:23.682 --> 10:25.764
Well, we have how long?

10:27.326 --> 10:29.889
I'll tell the very short version.

10:30.029 --> 10:32.111
I mean, don't be too short about it, but I'm right.

10:32.291 --> 10:34.113
Right, yeah.

10:34.133 --> 10:43.764
So as I mentioned, the guys and I went to Europe and coming out of Europe, we were trying to figure out where we wanted to go next.

10:44.264 --> 10:49.290
And we decided in 2018 that we would go to China.

10:49.991 --> 10:53.234
And part of our trip to China was to

10:53.602 --> 11:19.794
actually stay at an orphanage for kids with disabilities and that opportunity was so that we could encourage the staff and play with the kids and so we took some bunk beds there for a week and just did life with them which was really cool and Katie was working there at the time and so

11:20.514 --> 11:22.256
We met there.

11:22.336 --> 11:27.343
She was, last minute, put in charge of keeping us out of trouble.

11:27.903 --> 11:32.489
And if she was up here, she would add as long as we both shall live.

11:33.190 --> 11:37.155
And so we met then.

11:37.175 --> 11:44.184
And because she was in charge of us, we had a whole week of getting to know each other and hanging out.

11:44.344 --> 11:49.170
But she saw the guys

11:49.314 --> 11:54.059
you know, throwing me around and putting me on their backs and everything, no wheelchair.

11:54.139 --> 11:59.805
And so she thought, oh, Kevin's really cool, but I can't do that.

11:59.925 --> 12:08.154
And so, and I was just worried about one of the other guys falling in love with a girl and not coming home.

12:08.314 --> 12:16.242
So I wasn't even thinking about myself here, but at the end of that visit, I turned to

12:16.546 --> 12:22.752
My friend Ben, we got in the van and I turned to him and I said, I've never met anyone like her.

12:23.653 --> 12:27.857
And being boys, we were like, huh.

12:27.877 --> 12:31.340
Anyway, you know, we've done my time.

12:31.360 --> 12:33.843
And oh, that's a cool song on the radio, you know.

12:35.905 --> 12:45.554
But we stayed in touch for the next few months and got to talk a few times on the phone and invited each other into

12:45.794 --> 12:50.040
some deeper things that were going on in our separate lives.

12:50.201 --> 13:03.861
And it came to a point where a mutual friend of ours in the state had noticed that whenever we would each talk to her, we were talking about each other all the time.

13:04.542 --> 13:08.909
And so she came to me and said, have you ever thought about asking anyone out?

13:09.410 --> 13:10.972
It's like, yeah, of course.

13:11.092 --> 13:14.898
And she said, I think you should ask Katie out.

13:15.074 --> 13:19.960
And it was then that I realized that that's what I had wanted the whole time.

13:20.320 --> 13:29.131
And so, the next time we were, well, I took a month to pray about it, because she was in China.

13:30.573 --> 13:31.454
Side note, right?

13:31.954 --> 13:45.010
And so next time we texted at the end of that month, I said, by the way, could I take you out to dinner next time we're in the same country?

13:45.314 --> 13:46.495
And she said, yes.

13:47.397 --> 13:49.399
And do I keep going?

13:50.180 --> 13:53.144
Yeah, I feel like.

13:53.164 --> 13:54.445
OK. That's the new book.

13:54.465 --> 13:55.306
So we'll just wait.

13:55.487 --> 13:56.147
No, no.

13:56.648 --> 13:57.249
It's in the book.

13:57.489 --> 13:58.070
It's in the book.

13:58.090 --> 13:58.490
It's there.

14:00.933 --> 14:05.799
But yeah, so I had done some other speaking overseas.

14:05.859 --> 14:11.186
And so she said, well, I'm going to be in Australia in September.

14:11.298 --> 14:12.159
Just around the corner.

14:12.360 --> 14:15.224
If you happen to be speaking there, let me know.

14:15.885 --> 14:19.431
And I wasn't, but all I heard was the yes.

14:19.811 --> 14:30.849
And so I called my dad and a good friend of mine that had gone on the other trips and said, would you guys go to Australia with me?

14:31.429 --> 14:35.576
And so I called her and said, I'm there.

14:35.776 --> 14:36.537
I'm like, I want to go.

14:36.798 --> 14:39.442
And so September we met.

14:39.714 --> 14:43.337
September of 2018 in China, September of 2019.

14:44.939 --> 14:47.782
We met up in Sydney, Australia for our first date.

14:48.422 --> 14:54.708
And it was just a really cool experience, because we got to spend time together.

14:54.808 --> 14:57.190
But like my dad was there, my friend was there.

14:57.210 --> 14:59.072
They got to take care of me.

14:59.232 --> 15:03.496
And yeah, it was just a great experience.

15:03.596 --> 15:09.522
And fish and chips on the beach, not a bad first date.

15:09.634 --> 15:15.219
a year later, September of 2020, everybody's favorite year.

15:16.581 --> 15:24.308
We got married, and we have lived happily ever after for five years, and it's been incredible.

15:25.909 --> 15:26.610
Amen.

15:26.850 --> 15:29.853
Yeah, you can go.

15:32.956 --> 15:39.282
If I may, our dad too, that we were talking with someone about this earlier,

15:39.714 --> 15:46.822
speaking of the hospitality of need because of my needs.

15:47.623 --> 15:58.155
Now that we're married and KV is part of caregiving with me, our attachment and I think it's benefited our marriage.

15:58.315 --> 16:05.804
It's grown us deeper, faster, in some really wonderful ways, so we're both thankful for it.

16:06.785 --> 16:07.506
Amen, man.

16:08.034 --> 16:20.992
Well, in light of that, Tyler said you wrote a book called The Hospitality of Need, and I can testify to who you are and how I've seen your friends care for you and you care for them, and the beautiful love between you and your bride.

16:21.333 --> 16:26.059
So we'd love for you to unpack some of that book for us and invite us into a new way of living.

16:26.079 --> 16:27.221
Thanks, man.

16:27.241 --> 16:27.341
Yeah.

16:27.361 --> 16:30.065
Do you mind pulling my arm up before you go?

16:30.085 --> 16:30.386
Sure.

16:30.406 --> 16:30.766
I got you.

16:33.550 --> 16:34.011
There we go.

16:34.031 --> 16:34.291
Thanks.

16:35.272 --> 16:36.434
Cool.

16:37.186 --> 16:49.407
Yeah, I wanted to take some pieces of the book and just share some thoughts with you about the Kingdom of Heaven, if that's all right.

16:52.993 --> 17:02.930
Jesus said in Mark 10, 45, the Son of Man came not to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many.

17:04.226 --> 17:12.298
And he lived out this truth even as he asked the Samaritan for a drink of water and allowed a woman to wash his feet.

17:13.960 --> 17:27.781
In these and many other human needs, for he was full of God and fully man, he stooped himself well to serve, to ransom those who were on the surface serving him.

17:29.464 --> 17:33.810
Perhaps we should ask ourselves then what we are doing with our needs.

17:35.138 --> 17:37.521
Does looking out for number one ever get old to you?

17:38.503 --> 17:43.230
Our culture screams at us that this is what life is all about.

17:44.191 --> 17:46.474
But do you ever wonder if there might be something more?

17:49.198 --> 17:54.125
In a second letter to the Corinthians, Paul talks about our interactions with each other.

17:54.906 --> 18:03.218
And more than once, he says that we should be servants to each other and that everything we do should be for the sake of others.

18:03.938 --> 18:13.069
He's echoing what Jesus replied when James and John, who really, their mom, was vying for a seat beside Jesus in heaven.

18:13.129 --> 18:22.982
Paul gives us the big picture when he says, on the day of our Lord Jesus, you will boast of us as we will boast of you.

18:24.263 --> 18:32.914
Meaning that in the kingdom of heaven, we're going to be praising Jesus, and if we talk about anything else at all, it won't be ourselves.

18:33.474 --> 18:37.799
You will be writing about me, and I'll be going on and on about you.

18:37.819 --> 18:43.445
And even that will all be in the context of praising our Creator.

18:45.428 --> 18:54.378
The Bible is chock-full of this message that we should serve one another, putting others before ourselves, and laying our lives down for each other.

18:55.579 --> 19:01.746
Paul writes in Philippians 2, in humility, count others more significantly than yourselves.

19:02.146 --> 19:07.834
let each of you look not only to your own interest, but also to the interest of others.

19:08.956 --> 19:12.982
Have this mind among yourselves, which is yours in Christ Jesus.

19:13.984 --> 19:27.984
And then later he goes on to say, do all things without grumbling or disputing that you may be blameless and innocent children of God without blemish in the midst of a crooked and twisted generation.

19:29.907 --> 19:31.730
What I can't find in there

19:32.610 --> 19:44.205
as a caveat that I don't need to serve in the case where my need is greater or more obvious or more time-sensitive than that of my neighbor.

19:45.546 --> 19:47.589
So, what are we supposed to do?

19:49.131 --> 19:52.736
How do we serve one another despite our own needs?

19:54.298 --> 20:00.946
Perhaps it's not a matter of God using us to serve others despite our needs, but actually through them.

20:02.338 --> 20:10.427
Paul suggests this when he gives us a glimpse into his own need, and God's response to his desire to not have it.

20:12.009 --> 20:25.043
He says in 2 Corinthians 12 that the Lord told him, my power is made perfect in weakness, to which he concludes, I will boast all the more gladly of my weaknesses.

20:26.565 --> 20:31.250
It seems that it's all about our posture, our perspective,

20:31.682 --> 20:32.363
our perch.

20:34.305 --> 20:42.334
I'm reminded of Luke 18 when Jesus was playing with some kids, and his disciples didn't get it or like it.

20:43.315 --> 20:54.987
They scolded the children and their parents for bothering Jesus, and he retorted, let the little children come to me and do not hinder them, for to such belongs the kingdom of God.

20:55.988 --> 21:01.234
Truly, I say to you, whoever does not receive the kingdom of God like a child,

21:01.570 --> 21:02.811
shall not enter it.

21:04.973 --> 21:10.179
But Luke's account actually gives a little extra note that we should be careful not to gloss over.

21:11.080 --> 21:18.167
Because at the beginning, Luke actually says, now, they were bringing even infants to him.

21:18.207 --> 21:27.316
This stops me from my tracks because I actually have a lot of infant-like qualities in the scope of my own personal needs.

21:28.577 --> 21:29.618
I am an adult.

21:29.890 --> 21:39.539
I'm married, I pay taxes, I could do math in my head, buy airplane tickets, I can read GK Chesterton and understand most of it.

21:41.461 --> 21:43.102
But I have this disease.

21:43.303 --> 21:51.310
It's called spinal muscular atrophy, which means I rely fully on this wheelchair and the care of others.

21:52.451 --> 21:59.698
I need help using the restroom, showering, getting dressed, preparing food, sometimes eating that food,

21:59.842 --> 22:07.010
opening doors, blowing my nose, scratching my head run at itches, getting my arm up here to scroll this iPad.

22:08.052 --> 22:12.897
And if I'm not in my wheelchair, I can't move or hold myself upright.

22:13.938 --> 22:20.987
I may be 39 years old, but my autonomy is about as extensive as that of a newborn baby.

22:23.810 --> 22:27.474
Usually when I read this scene in Luke 18,

22:28.098 --> 22:35.905
I imagine a bunch of wiry kids, around eight or nine years old, barefoot, with their behind their ears.

22:37.387 --> 22:41.351
A whole bunch of them come running and dogpiled themselves under Jesus.

22:42.351 --> 22:47.616
He laughs, wrestles with them, plays tag, tells them stories on his knee.

22:49.258 --> 22:51.400
And I don't doubt that this happened too.

22:52.861 --> 22:57.746
But Luke's account is specifically, it seems, about newborn babies.

22:58.274 --> 23:00.997
And newborn babies can't do much at all.

23:03.259 --> 23:14.749
So often our analogy is that we should come to Jesus like kids come up to their parents, trusting them to provide wisdom, safety, comfort, care, nourishment.

23:16.551 --> 23:17.932
And there is truth to this.

23:19.374 --> 23:28.082
But we're still talking about a child walking up, tugging on his dad's pants leg, looking up, and asking for these things.

23:29.410 --> 23:38.761
Whether we realize it or not, we tend to assume a bit more workspace-faith than our walk with the Lord than we might realize or care to admit.

23:41.604 --> 23:43.847
What about when we can't walk up to our dad?

23:45.028 --> 23:51.736
What about when we are at the end of our strength and can't even reach out to touch the hem of Jesus' garment?

23:53.237 --> 23:57.202
What about when our shame let us look up into his eyes and ask?

23:58.722 --> 24:09.919
As someone with a disabled body and an equally disabled soul, I am in desperate need of a rescuer coming to get me, more so than a home plate to run to.

24:09.939 --> 24:16.249
I was once an intern at a prison ministry in Arkansas.

24:17.731 --> 24:23.000
God did some amazing things in my life and the lives of the inmates around me that summer.

24:23.500 --> 24:27.186
But my last week there, it started to rain.

24:28.066 --> 24:29.568
And I don't mean figuratively.

24:31.149 --> 24:35.253
I mean we had a good old-fashioned southern summer storm.

24:35.313 --> 24:42.821
The kind that's so massive and relentless that you begin to wonder if this is just how it is from now on.

24:42.861 --> 24:47.766
Gray, as far as you can see, and rain until Jesus comes back.

24:48.427 --> 24:50.589
But I had a job to do.

24:51.129 --> 24:52.751
So I showed up at the prison gates.

24:53.952 --> 24:55.794
Going from building to building

24:56.002 --> 25:05.372
I readied myself like Benny, the Jack Rodriguez, cracking my knuckles, stealing myself for the run of my life through what seemed like a waterfall.

25:06.513 --> 25:09.977
My wheelchair cut like a knife through puddle six inches deep.

25:10.658 --> 25:19.447
Familiar faces threw up in the doors to our building as I coasted inside, sliding to a stop on the concrete floor.

25:21.490 --> 25:25.554
I was instantly surrounded by a congregation of white jumpsuits.

25:26.274 --> 25:34.223
Inmates I had worked with all summer, came around me with piles of fresh cows to dry off my body, clothes, and wheelchair.

25:35.504 --> 25:41.771
Men convicted of assault, gently dried my hair and face, and bent down to warm up my legs.

25:42.792 --> 25:47.417
Former drug dealers stopped up the pools on my armrest and seat.

25:48.578 --> 25:55.506
They learned me a white jumpsuit while my clothes were drying, and we joked that the guards wouldn't let me out at the end of the day.

25:56.226 --> 25:56.646
They did.

25:56.686 --> 26:04.154
What's more, my motors on my chair turned out to be waterlogged.

26:05.476 --> 26:10.601
My chair was rendered useless and not meant that in many ways, so was I.

26:10.621 --> 26:17.749
For the next four days, while at work, I was fully dependent on society's outcast.

26:19.030 --> 26:22.674
I never thought I would have to mediate arguments between inmates

26:22.818 --> 26:26.924
over who would be next in line to push my 400 pound wheelchair.

26:28.446 --> 26:37.117
If I didn't feel helpless enough already though, with a body that didn't work, this was a whole new level that I wasn't thrilled about.

26:38.499 --> 26:49.394
But this is where God rolled up his sleeves and started having some fun, calling us to himself not in spite of my shortcomings, but actually through them.

26:51.746 --> 26:59.896
My friends and I had gotten to know each other over the summer, praying and studying the scriptures together, telling jokes, talking about life.

27:01.058 --> 27:05.704
We had delved deeply into heart matters and reconstructed our ways of thinking.

27:05.764 --> 27:11.070
Most of what we worked on was preparation or theory, in a way.

27:11.090 --> 27:14.615
How will I love my wife when I get out of prison?

27:14.655 --> 27:16.898
How will I nurture my kids?

27:17.619 --> 27:20.242
How will I commit to my job and work hard?

27:21.218 --> 27:32.635
In prison, we could work on submitting to authority and logging our neighbor to an extent, but even those things looked different in that culture than they were on the outside.

27:34.618 --> 27:47.538
But we did a lot of talking together, a lot of work and a lot of play, and then this meag arose, my meag, this new one that made infants look like Jason Bourne.

27:48.994 --> 28:00.733
All that internal work we had been doing suddenly turned outward, allowing hands and feet the opportunity to act upon what hearts had been learning all along.

28:00.773 --> 28:09.727
Our theory of how the love one another took on flesh and became a reality for us to grow in and flourish.

28:10.848 --> 28:14.354
And we found ourselves in the midst of the kingdom of heaven.

28:15.810 --> 28:22.478
A group of guys lowered their crippled friend through a roof to get to Jesus, and Jesus commended their faith.

28:23.500 --> 28:28.907
He saddled up next to a lame beggar by a pool and offered uncomfortably to heal him.

28:30.268 --> 28:40.461
And as he cradled a newborn baby and his carpenter arms, he essentially said to his disciples, if you don't approach the kingdom like this, you won't get in.

28:42.724 --> 28:44.146
I find comfort in this.

28:44.834 --> 28:52.024
that he calls us to come as helpless as a newborn baby, not even big enough for strong enough to crawl.

28:52.885 --> 29:01.698
Carried to him or found by him, our total dead weight held in his arms because we can't help at all.

29:02.960 --> 29:04.882
Maybe that's exactly where he wants us.

29:07.005 --> 29:09.689
One of my favorite authors is a guy named S.D.

29:09.789 --> 29:10.290
Smith.

29:10.946 --> 29:14.512
And if you have kids in middle school, they would love his books.

29:14.532 --> 29:19.220
But there's a recurring theme that I really love in several of his books.

29:19.340 --> 29:25.670
It's a question that he poses through a teacher to a student.

29:26.492 --> 29:31.680
They'll be training the student in the last, what do you have on hand to use as a weapon?

29:31.720 --> 29:37.650
Typically, the student will list off his sword, maybe his fist or his feet.

29:39.042 --> 29:45.050
Then the teacher will shake his head and list off 10 other things around him that he could have used.

29:45.630 --> 29:50.977
That branch, that bike pedal, his shoe, his opponent's size or momentum.

29:54.742 --> 29:59.808
So let's ask ourselves what we have on hand to help others in need.

30:01.090 --> 30:07.858
When asking this, most of us will list money or strength or some specific skill to offer.

30:08.898 --> 30:15.645
And if we don't have those, we ride ourselves off as useless or in greater need than the other.

30:15.665 --> 30:29.901
I promise I'm not shaking my head at you, but I do challenge you to look again because maybe, just maybe, you'll find something that you should have listed among our assets in the first place.

30:30.782 --> 30:34.226
Namely, your own weaknesses and needs

30:35.618 --> 30:52.959
And what we will find when we lean into this hospitality that need offers is that it is an antidote for isolation, self-centeredness, and impotent Christianity.

30:54.381 --> 31:05.394
As my friend Jed Medifen put it when breaking down the antidote for all these three illnesses, the hospitality of need, being an antidote for isolation,

31:05.954 --> 31:18.293
We ache to belong, but do not understand that belonging is woven, especially with countless threads of mutual responsibility and sacrifice.

31:19.235 --> 31:25.765
Caring for others' needs and sharing our own nits us together as nothing else can.

31:26.907 --> 31:33.938
It draws us out from the lonely dens where we peer at the world and others through screens.

31:34.626 --> 31:41.156
caregiving demands face to face, hand to hand, touch and sweat and sometimes blood.

31:42.037 --> 31:47.926
It wakes us from our device fed stupor and puts an end to our tragic seclusion.

31:49.869 --> 32:03.730
The hospitality of need being an antidote for self-centeredness, the dance of giving and receiving takes us in precisely the opposite direction of selfishness and its pitfalls.

32:04.578 --> 32:11.629
It reorients not only our outward actions, but also critically our thought life too.

32:11.669 --> 32:23.687
Any mindset, counselor, or therapy that turns our attention mainly to ourselves will yield only anxiety and unhappiness in the long run.

32:24.748 --> 32:33.842
Slowly and lifting our eyes beyond ourselves to God and to others are we freed from the terrible burden of self-focus.

32:34.594 --> 32:39.360
In Christ, we trade it for the light yoke of self-forgetfulness.

32:41.764 --> 32:56.984
In the hospitality of need as an antidote for shallow and potent Christianity, whenever we followed Jesus into one another's need, joining him there in the dance of mutual care, we never emerged the same.

32:58.246 --> 33:04.114
We are formed anew, especially by small choices, frequently repeated

33:04.386 --> 33:07.029
steadily growing more like Jesus.

33:09.111 --> 33:17.218
And we experience this hospitality, this antidote by going to the source in prayer and obedience to God.

33:18.680 --> 33:28.750
We must ask Him to help us see our own needs more clearly and invite others into them and to see and respond to others' needs more fully too.

33:30.111 --> 33:33.394
And once we've since God pointing us toward an action,

33:33.890 --> 33:36.253
We must give no place for delay.

33:36.313 --> 33:47.289
God designed us to rely on him and not just on him but on one another as a means of pointing each other and the world to him.

33:47.329 --> 33:57.203
Need is one of the instruments God has given us on which to play our testimony of who he is and what he has done.

33:57.243 --> 34:02.450
This is the case whether we are stepping into someone else's need

34:02.786 --> 34:05.349
or inviting someone into our own.

34:06.571 --> 34:14.141
In Galatians 6-2, Paul tells us to bear one another's burdens and so fulfill the law of Christ.

34:15.984 --> 34:25.637
We live in a culture obsessed with self-advocacy and self-care, but those routes are desolate and will leave us empty and alone.

34:25.657 --> 34:32.466
I think that picture that Paul paints back in 2nd Corinthians is pretty amazing.

34:33.250 --> 34:40.237
As believers, a day will come for us when our selfishness will melt away in the presence of Jesus.

34:41.258 --> 34:45.041
And our focus will be solely on him and everyone else.

34:46.442 --> 34:53.389
And the things of earth will grow strangely dim, including maybe especially ourselves.

34:55.511 --> 35:02.898
We won't be weighed down anymore by the worries of our own

35:03.106 --> 35:05.349
preservation or accolades.

35:06.210 --> 35:12.099
We will never again be scared, proud, jealous, annoyed, lustful, or greedy.

35:12.700 --> 35:16.345
The last of us will be first, and the first will be last.

35:16.986 --> 35:21.733
And we will weep with laughter to see who exactly that ends up being.

35:21.793 --> 35:28.242
He drives this point home in Colossians 1 when he says to the church,

35:28.450 --> 35:43.513
We always thank God the Father of our Lord Jesus Christ when we pray for you, since we heard of your faith in Christ Jesus and of the love you have for all the saints because of the hope played up for you in heaven.

35:45.536 --> 35:47.058
And can I tell you something odd?

35:47.118 --> 35:51.164
I don't think we'll miss being selfish at all.

35:53.087 --> 35:57.554
I don't even think it will be a word or a memory to us in that marvelous city

35:58.178 --> 36:04.968
And if some greasy peddler could sneak in and whisper it into our ears, we would swat him away like an ant.

36:06.330 --> 36:09.434
That's what Jesus' presence does.

36:09.454 --> 36:11.537
It turns our priorities on their heads.

36:12.599 --> 36:17.586
He makes us whole so that there is nothing left to advocate for ourselves.

36:18.928 --> 36:26.098
And in that wholeness, we are set free to turn our full attention on him and on others.

36:27.618 --> 36:29.381
And can I tell you one more odd thing?

36:29.421 --> 36:38.334
This is the life he has called us to, not just on streets of gold far off in the future, but here and now.

36:40.077 --> 36:49.251
It will be made perfect in the end because sin will be out of the way, but we still have the Holy Spirit now, and Jesus said he's with us too.

36:50.353 --> 36:56.242
So let us live in the wholeness of his presence, behold his glory,

36:56.802 --> 36:58.684
and put others before ourselves.

36:59.865 --> 37:06.333
This is where we will find satisfaction, rest, and peace together.

37:21.570 --> 37:25.234
I want to give you just a little bit more of a picture of how that plays out between us

37:25.730 --> 37:27.712
and then maybe a quick encouragement.

37:29.995 --> 37:52.562
You know, Kevin, his sister Connie has SMA also, and she started attending our fellowship back in Fort Wayne, and we really got invited in to need through our relationship with her, and it became one of the more precious relationships, but Kevin would come and visit here and there, and as he visited, we sparked a relationship, and as we sparked that relationship,

37:53.506 --> 37:55.689
Things kind of became more and more beautiful.

37:56.450 --> 38:10.589
Oftentimes, Kevin, who would be in this apartment or this house with these other guys, would be found walking, riding, rolling down the street of our downtown, finding the next new coffee shop they could sit in, talk to someone, listen to their story.

38:10.609 --> 38:15.096
And he really became this constant presence in places that needed presence.

38:15.817 --> 38:16.818
That makes any sense.

38:18.210 --> 38:21.354
He would leave his signature drawn by another friend.

38:21.374 --> 38:27.723
It might be Batman who bought that coffee drink or Superman or Spiderman, leaving his imprint wherever he went.

38:27.783 --> 38:29.125
It was gorgeous.

38:31.327 --> 38:37.135
Then we moved to Maine to plant churches and be a part of the city there and then moved back.

38:38.477 --> 38:45.266
My wife was just like, hey, can we get a spot that's a little bit out of the fray so that you're not running into the fire all the time?

38:46.370 --> 38:49.713
I said, well, I'm not super comfortable with that, but we can try.

38:49.753 --> 38:53.176
And so we find this house in the suburbs.

38:54.658 --> 38:57.020
And then Kevin and I start hanging out again.

38:57.040 --> 39:01.324
And one day he said, hey, man, would you come over and get me ready for the day?

39:03.146 --> 39:10.833
And like I said yesterday, it was absolutely your friend, your brother, and I'm your neighbor.

39:11.674 --> 39:15.858
And Jesus has invited me to love you, just like you're going to love me.

39:16.194 --> 39:18.036
Now I had no idea what that would turn into.

39:20.099 --> 39:28.691
But what was crazy was where we bought our house was probably a 90 second drive, a four minute walk from his house, him and Katie's house.

39:28.791 --> 39:30.573
And so I'd get in my big truck.

39:30.594 --> 39:32.696
If you've ever seen the big truck, it's too big for me.

39:33.798 --> 39:35.400
And it came that way.

39:35.440 --> 39:39.826
I did not supercharge that sucker to look like something, but many people make jokes about it.

39:40.482 --> 39:42.544
I jump in, jump out, and we call that a day.

39:42.704 --> 39:47.570
And so I would drive around the corner up the driveway where the door would be cracked.

39:49.712 --> 39:56.300
The welcome was already set before I pulled in the driveway, knowing that I was going to a place where I belonged.

39:57.121 --> 40:05.590
And so I'd walk through that front door, drop my keys, kick off my shoes, knowing that there'd be a coffee with some special sauce that I would get to add to it made by Katie.

40:06.751 --> 40:09.234
Then I would turn to the left past the piano

40:09.410 --> 40:21.528
to another door that was cracked, where she would be sitting there normally with the Bible, another book, in her lap, and then Kevin just waking up from his slumber, normally growling, as I said, what it is.

40:21.548 --> 40:24.592
And he was angry, what it is.

40:24.652 --> 40:31.903
And I'd walk in there, and we spend about 20, 30 minutes breaking down life for one another.

40:32.865 --> 40:39.314
And what I want to do, just for a few minutes, is invite you to see a picture of what he just

40:39.650 --> 40:40.351
spoke about.

40:42.714 --> 40:47.019
So as I walked in there, there were several things I'd have to do to get to him ready for the day.

40:48.841 --> 40:51.224
But one part was to get him to the bathroom.

40:52.105 --> 40:58.533
And as I would get him to the bathroom, what would be interesting for me is I went to serve Kevin's needs.

40:59.935 --> 41:05.682
My whole goal that morning, every morning of every week, or that morning of every week was to simply serve him.

41:07.202 --> 41:12.650
But as I got him ready for the bathroom and sat on the edge of their bed, he began to ask me questions about myself.

41:14.613 --> 41:15.334
How are you doing, man?

41:17.176 --> 41:17.998
What's going on with you?

41:20.241 --> 41:20.902
How's your wife?

41:21.883 --> 41:22.564
How are your kids?

41:24.467 --> 41:25.228
How's leadership?

41:27.091 --> 41:27.692
How's your heart?

41:30.616 --> 41:34.802
And what I started watching was this invitation to serve as need began to be

41:35.010 --> 41:37.896
an invitation for him to serve my needs just like he spoke about.

41:39.198 --> 41:45.370
And eventually this invitation to serve his need was twisted for him to serve my need.

41:45.550 --> 41:57.874
Before long, simply all we were doing was sharing our need, our wholeness and friendship and brotherhood and kinship and what kind of melted away was the reason that I was there and the reason that was he was there was simply for each other.

41:59.170 --> 42:01.612
And for three and a half years, that was our morning rhythm.

42:01.672 --> 42:05.556
And randomly, he would give me a call or a text and say, hey, bro, could you get over here right now?

42:05.636 --> 42:06.897
I need to serve Katie.

42:06.917 --> 42:07.698
I need you to get over here.

42:07.718 --> 42:10.180
And I would peel over around the corner and get to do that.

42:10.481 --> 42:11.462
It wasn't about me.

42:11.562 --> 42:19.029
It was about the invitation of kinship or brotherhood, where we depended on one another, related to one another, and gave our lives away for one another.

42:20.330 --> 42:23.913
And like I said before, the greatest miss.

42:23.993 --> 42:24.734
I miss my kids.

42:24.794 --> 42:25.635
I miss my grandkids.

42:25.655 --> 42:28.978
Those are all rhythms that I long for and desire regularly.

42:31.490 --> 42:38.140
But the one that pierced my heart and molded me most was walking into Kevin's need and his walking into mind.

42:40.563 --> 42:45.651
And so I just wanna quickly give you a few thoughts of what I think could happen if we enter into each other's needs.

42:47.514 --> 42:52.281
In John 13, 34 through 35 is a new command that Jesus gives us.

42:54.905 --> 42:57.488
He says, you know, as the Father's love me, I've loved you.

42:59.892 --> 43:01.234
If you would love one another,

43:01.602 --> 43:03.444
All people will know you're my disciples.

43:03.544 --> 43:04.705
Buy your love for one another.

43:06.987 --> 43:10.931
About five years ago, another man said to me, it's reciprocal love.

43:10.971 --> 43:12.152
It's giving and receiving.

43:13.053 --> 43:15.896
And most relationships, we only have one valve on.

43:15.916 --> 43:17.418
We either give or we receive.

43:18.959 --> 43:29.970
But what if the body was built off of people who give and receive in the midst of need and through our need back and forth to one another, just like the Father, the Son, and the Spirit?

43:31.298 --> 43:43.431
His promise is this, that if you would do like the Father and me and the Spirit, if you would live in this dance with this love, that all people would know you're my apprentices.

43:46.334 --> 43:48.036
The whole world would know you're my people.

43:49.498 --> 43:54.884
He carries that thought on at the end of this upper room discourse in John 17, 21, and 24.

43:55.184 --> 44:00.690
He said, man, if you would be one, like the Father, the Son, and the Spirit, if you would be one,

44:02.658 --> 44:04.701
people would believe that I was sent by the Father.

44:05.922 --> 44:10.108
It's the gospel.

44:10.128 --> 44:32.498
Not only that we're his apprentices or his followers or his disciples, but that Jesus actually came as a man, lived a real life, walked to the cross with joy before him, was buried in a grave, resurrected on the third day, ascended to the right hand of majesty, that that would be believed by our reciprocal love for one another.

44:34.338 --> 44:36.882
And lastly, he would carry on in verse 24 and say this.

44:38.846 --> 44:43.554
If you would be one as we are one, they would believe that the Father loves the world.

44:47.641 --> 44:49.143
I just want you to think about that for a minute.

44:49.944 --> 44:57.938
Because what Kevin has displayed and invited me into and now is inviting us into has this incredible promise tied to it.

44:59.106 --> 45:06.618
that if we had come in our weakness and in our need and give and receive love back and forth through such need, that the world would know that we're His people.

45:08.942 --> 45:10.985
That Jesus actually came and did what He said He would do.

45:12.768 --> 45:18.957
And that the Father actually loves the world.

45:18.977 --> 45:24.466
And why I say all that is because I sat in a room with a buddy for a handful of years,

45:25.506 --> 45:28.750
And what I thought I was going for wasn't what I was actually going for.

45:28.810 --> 45:35.277
I was actually learning how to do community life in kinship with someone in a way that I had never learned before.

45:38.300 --> 45:44.407
And so I don't know what the spirit might say to you tonight, but I can tell you that this brother has taught me and informed me in a new way of walking with Jesus.

45:44.467 --> 45:49.133
And my prayer is for him and I and all of us here that we'd walk that way all the way home.

45:51.275 --> 45:53.778
And so before Tyler and Bethany come back on up here,

45:54.370 --> 45:56.972
I would love for him to bless us and pray over us.

45:58.234 --> 46:00.296
And maybe give any last final thoughts that you might have.

46:03.679 --> 46:04.019
You good?

46:04.179 --> 46:05.621
Yeah.

46:05.641 --> 46:11.906
Yeah.

46:11.926 --> 46:17.712
Father, I pray for this community, pray for these friends, this family.

46:21.155 --> 46:24.338
Lord, as they step into

46:24.546 --> 46:26.909
what you have called them to be.

46:28.250 --> 46:33.697
That you will give them boldness, that you will give them humility, and you will give them joy.

46:33.737 --> 46:37.802
Yeah, so you blessed them in that.

46:41.666 --> 46:51.538
And now, to him, my crew is able to keep you from stumbling and to present you blameless before the presence of his glory with great joy.

46:52.450 --> 47:13.502
So the only God our Savior through Jesus Christ, our Lord, be glory and majesty, dominion and authority before all time and now and forever may he bless you and keep you and make his face to shine upon you and be gracious to you.

47:14.844 --> 47:20.052
May he turn his face toward you and give you a peace that passes understanding.

47:21.293 --> 47:21.714
Amen.

47:22.210 --> 47:22.803
Thank you.

